# Employee Performance Dashboard

##  Project Overview
This project presents an interactive Employee Dashboard built using Microsoft Excel.  
The dashboard provides a comprehensive overview of workforce analytics including employee distribution, salary insights, department breakdown, and years of service.
It helps HR teams and management make data-driven decisions regarding workforce planning and compensation strategy.
[Dashboard Preview](Employee Performance Dashboard.JPG)

##  Objectives
- Analyze total workforce distribution
- Identify active vs inactive employees
- Evaluate salary structure and top paid employees
- Analyze average years of service by job role
- Understand employee age distribution

## Key Metrics
- Total Employees: 792
- Active Employees: 691
- Inactive Employees: 101
- Average Years of Service: 2.68
- Average Annual Salary: $661,108.71

##  Dashboard Components
### 1️⃣ Employee Count per Department
- Engineering represents the largest workforce segment.
- IT and Finance follow in workforce distribution.
### 2️⃣ Age Year of Service Analysis
- Dev Engineering and Quality Engineering show higher service averages.
- IT Coordination shows the lowest average service years.
### 3️⃣ Top 10 High Paid Employees
- Displays highest earning employees.
- Useful for compensation benchmarking.
### 4️⃣ Employee Age Distribution
- Majority workforce lies in the 30–39 age group.
- Balanced gender representation across age groups.

##  Tools Used
- Microsoft Excel
  - Pivot Tables
  - Slicers
  - Charts
  - Dashboard Design Techniques

##  Business Insights
- Engineering department dominates headcount (over 50%).
- Workforce is relatively young (majority under 40).
- Certain technical roles show higher retention (based on service years).
- Compensation concentration among specific job roles.

##  Recommendations
- Develop retention strategies for low service-year roles.
- Plan succession strategy based on age distribution.
- Conduct salary structure review for fairness and competitiveness.
- Focus on career progression in high-density departments.

